{{Cleanup FJC Bio}}
'''Richard D. Bennett''' (born 1947) is a [[United States federal judge]].

Bennett was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. He received a [[B.A.]] from [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1969. He received a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[University of Maryland School of Law]] in 1973. He was in the [[United States Army]] Reserve from 1969 to 1975. He was a Maryland Army National Guard from 1983 to 1997. He was in private practice of law in [[Maryland, 1973-1976, 1981-1991]] from 1993 to 2003. He was an Assistant U.S. attorney of District of Maryland from 1976 to 1980. He was a U.S. Attorney for the District of Maryland from 1991 to 1993. 

Bennett was a federal judge to the [[United States District Court for the District of Maryland]]. Bennett was nominated by President [[George W. Bush]] on January 29, 2003, to a seat vacated by [[Frederic N. Smalkin]]. He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on April 9, 2003, and received commission on April 10, 2003. 

